===Etymology 1===
From {{etyl|zh|en}} {{m|zh|上海||Shanghai|tr=Shànghǎi}}, with reference to the former practice of forcibly crewing ships heading for the [[Orient]].

====Verb====
{{en-verb}}

# {{lb|en|transitive}} To force or trick (someone) into joining a ship which is lacking a full crew.
#* '''1999''' June 24, ‘The Resurrection of Tom Waits’, in ''Rolling Stone'', quoted in ''Innocent When You Dream'', Orion (2006), page 256,
#*: It was the strangest galley: the sounds, the steam, he's screaming at his coworkers. I felt like I'd been '''shanghaied'''.
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To abduct or coerce.
#* '''1974''' September 30, ‘[http://www.xfamily.org/index.php/Final_Report_on_the_Activities_of_the_Children_of_God#4._Attitude_Toward_Education Final Report on the Activities of the Children of God]',
#*: Oftentimes the approach is to '''shanghai''' an unsuspecting victim.
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[commandeer]]; [[appropriate]]; [[hijack]]
#: ''Let's see if we can '''shanghai''' a room for a couple of hours.''

